Soil Domestication

Joe Edwards

Introductions

Here in this experiment, we have grown rice plants in soils from rice fields and from locations that are adjacent to rice fields, but are not growing crops. The goal was to see if there are consistent differences between the microbiomes that rice plants assemble from these soils.

Load in the libraries

Note that this analysis relies on the tidyMB package. This can be found on my github profile.

Betadiversity

First things first. What is the underlying structure of the data?

Comparing rhizosphere to bulk soil distances

Remember that result where the rice rhizosphere is significantly more similar to the bulk soil microbiome than the rhizosphere microbiomes from the native plants? One of the hypotheses that came from that was that rice may be domesticating the soil microbiome. If you go to rice field, you will quickly realize that those plants are growing so closely together that, at some point in the season, there all of the roots will overlap and the top layer of soil is only composed of rhizosphere. We can test this hypothesis by growing rice plants in soil from rice fields and soil from uncultivated sites. In order to support this hypothesis that rice is domesticating field soil, we need to show a few things. One is that the distance between rhizospehre and bulk soil is greater in the wild soils. The other is that the rhizospheres of rice plants growing in wild and domesticated soils are mmore similar than the bulk soils.

The above plot appears to support my suspicion that rice plants growing in agricultural soil host a rhizosphere microbiome that is more similar to their corresponding bulk soils. Lets do some statistics to make sure these differences are signficant.

Cool Cool. Looks lik this trend is significant. Lets compare the rhizospheres to see if they are more similar.

grid.arrange(rs_vs_bs_plot, same_comps_plot, ncol = 2)

Differentially abundant OTUs

We see relatively large differences between domesticated and wild soils. Lets find the OTUs that explain these differences.

dom_deseq <- dExp %>% 
  group_by(variable) %>% 
  filter(sum(value > 0) / n() > 0.1) %>% 
  mutate(group = paste(Compartment, From, sep = ".")) %>% 
  group_by(group_var = "DESeq2", Experiment) %>% 
  nest() %>% 
  mutate(DGEL = map(data, ~suppressMessages(tidyDGEL(., value = "value", group_column = "group", method = "DESeq2", formula = "~ group")))) %>% 
  mutate(dds = map(DGEL, ~suppressMessages(DESeq(.)))) %>% 
  mutate(BulkSoil = map(dds, ~lfcShrink(., contrast = c("group", "Bulk Soil.A", "Bulk Soil.N")))) %>% 
  mutate(Rhizosphere = map(dds, ~lfcShrink(., contrast = c("group", "Rhizosphere.A", "Rhizosphere.N")))) %>% 
  mutate(Endosphere = map(dds, ~lfcShrink(., contrast = c("group", "Endosphere.A", "Endosphere.N")))) %>% 
  dplyr::select(BulkSoil, Rhizosphere, Endosphere, Experiment) %>% 
  gather(key = Compartment, value = results, -Experiment)

dom_deseq %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  write_rds(path = "~/RMB/SoilDomestication/Data/domestication_deseq.rds")

What is the overlap of rice enriched microbes with the domesticated microbes?

nA <- length(unique(rice_otus$variable))
nB <- length(unique(dom_otus %>% filter(direction == "A") %>% pull(variable)))
nC <- length(union(nExp %>% group_by(variable) %>% filter(sum(value) > 0) %>% dplyr::count(variable) %>% pull(variable),
          dExp %>% group_by(variable) %>% filter(sum(value) > 0) %>% dplyr::count(variable) %>% pull(variable)))
nAB <- length(intersect(dom_otus$variable, rice_otus$variable))

prob <- phyper(nAB, nB, nC-nB, nA, lower.tail = F)

There are 261 rice enriched microbes (compared to the weeds) and 158 OTUs that are enriched at least in one compartment of the plants growing in domesticated soils. Between the rice vs.weeds dataset and the soil domestication dataset, there are 13969 OTUs. There are 53 OTUs shared between the rice enriched and domesticated microbes. What is the probability that we whitness and overlap of 53 OTUs given these parameters? We can treat this like the trusty old black and white balls in an urn analogy. If we have an urn filled with 13969, and 158 of these balls are black and the rest are white, what is the probability that if we draw 261 balls from the urn that 53 of the balls will be black? We can use the hypergeometric function to figure out. After doing this calculation, we find that the probability of having an overlap of 53 between the datasets is 2.324520610^{-54}.

We have this nice overlap. Lets show it in tree form.

widen2 <- function(x, samples = "SampleID", otus = "variable", value = "RA", return_df = FALSE){
    message("Converting to wide table.")
    wide_table <- x %>% 
        dplyr::select_(samples, otus, value) %>% 
        tidyr::spread_(otus, value, fill = 0) %>% 
      ungroup()
    if(return_df) {
      df_row_names <- wide_table %>% dplyr::select_(samples) %>% pull()
      wide_table <- wide_table %>% dplyr::select_(.dots = paste("-", samples))
        wide_table = as.data.frame(wide_table)
        row.names(wide_table) <- df_row_names
        return(wide_table)
    } else {
        return(wide_table)
    }
}
